Answer: There are a couple of options to help you with CSRF.

\section{CSRF Protection}

The first option is to use the [TurboGears2 CSRF protection](https://github.com/TurboGears/tg2-features/tree/master/csrf).

The package is available for download on [PyPI](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/tg.csrf/0.1.2) and can be installed with `pip install tg.csrf`. It is a plugin that adds CSRF protection to the `tg.validate` decorator, which is the same decorator that TurboGears uses to validate forms.

\section{CSRF Protection Without Plugin}

The other option is to protect against CSRF without the use of a plugin. This method has the advantage of being able to use it in any project, not just a TurboGears 2 project.

You need to add the [CSRF token](https://github.com/TurboGears/tg2-features/blob/master/csrf/csrf.py#L112) to your forms, and then check that the token is valid in your controller.

\section{Example}

The `csrf.py` file in the turbogears2-csrf package can be used as an example.

\section{Add CSRF token to the form}

The first step is to add the CSRF token to the form. You can do this by adding a hidden field to the form, or you can add it to the \begin{code}
<form>
\end{code} tag itself.

\section{A hidden field}

\begin{code}
<input type="hidden" name="_csrf_token" value="{{ csrf_token }}">
\end{code}

\section{The form tag}

\begin{code}
<form action="/my/path" method="post" data-csrf="{{ csrf_token }}">
\end{code}

\section{Check the CSRF token in the controller}

The next step is to check that the CSRF token is valid in the controller. There are two ways to do this.

\section{Using `tg.flash`}

\begin{code}
from tg import flash

def my_controller(self, csrf_token):
    if not csrf_token:
        flash("CSRF Error")
        return
\end{code}

\section{Using a `try-except` block}

\begin{code}
from tg import expose, flash

def my_controller(self, csrf_token):
    try:
        csrf.validate_token(csrf_token)
    except ValueError:
        flash("CSRF Error")
\end{code}

\section{Add CSRF token to the template}

The last step is to get the CSRF token in the template. This is done using the `csrf_token` variable.

\begin{code}
{{ csrf_token }}
\end{code}

\section{Example}

The `csrf.py` file in the turbogears2-csrf package can be used as an example.

